 violence of the last decade over issues of immigration and of Muslims in the West, the results of this study demonstrate that the largest number of citizens in contemporary liberal democracies are more open to inclusion of Muslims than has been recognized. Not less important, the book reveals limits on inclusion that follow from the friction between liberal democratic values. This pioneering work thus brings to light both pathways to progress and polarization traps.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMuslimsxCultural assimilationzEurope. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apolitics, democracy, public opinion, liberal values, survey experiments, Muslims, Europe, minorities, inclusion, tolerance.1 aSniderman, Paul M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226807386423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226807386/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles